Tomorrow morning YOU can experience the excitement & adrenaline of conservation work at home...(link in bio to join in 🙌)
My good buddy Dr. Joel @the_conservation_vet is working with the @blueskysociety to collar African elephants in the greater Kruger area and if you purchase tickets to see this process live you’re actually making a donation to help out wild elephants 😁. Collaring Wild elephants requires helicopters, intensive veterinary care, and lots of feet on the ground AKA it’s pretty expensive. The real value in collaring comes from the scientific, ecologically significant research to follow, helping prevent human:wildlife conflict (which is massively important regarding elephants), and influencing policy to better protect our wildlife & habitats. 
I put a link in my bio if you’d like to see this crazy process from home and help the elephants in doing so. 
And give Dr. Joel ( @the_conservation_vet ) here a “happy birthday” for me tomorrow because this guy is collaring elephants on his birthday 🥳🔥❗️
#elephant #wildlife #conservation #research #humanwildlifeconflict #policy #🌍 #🇿🇦

You squeamish❓
Viewer discretion if sharp objects + eyeballs isn’t for you 👨🏻‍⚕️💁🏻‍♂️.
Eyelid tumors are typically benign tissue types however even benign tumors can become concerning if: 1. They protrude inward and contact the cornea, potentially damaging it with regular blinking 2. Their size or shape distorts healthy lid conformation and/or blinking 3. They grow too big, greater than 1/3rd the span of an upper or lower lid, because if it continues to grow and potentially eventually affect corneal health or blinking they’re much more complicated to remove when they’re occupying 1/3rd or more of eyelid width. 
Henry’s lid mass was not causing problems at this time but because of it’s increasing size and close proximity to a tear duct & tear gland I wanted to excise it (aka remove it) before it has a chance to become a more complicated surgery. Luckily surgery went well, Henry’s dental went well (only 2 incisors extracted) and his recovery was smooth. 
For fellow vets & nerds: I used hydromorphone 0.1 mg/kg premed and induced with midazolam 0.25 mg/kg followed by ketamine 5 mg/kg IV. I’ve used alfaxan & propofol for geriatric patients but I find that if their metabolic health is fine, heart health is normal to mild valvular disease, I like ketamine better for consistent gas/iso anesthesia %/levels and favorable blood pressure & heart rate. I use the exact same protocol in most young & middle aged dogs too (assuming they’re otherwise in good health). 
Suture: 4-0 Vicryl (braided, absorbable) Situational Pros: suture tags are soft & gentle on cornea, low memory, nice handling; Cons: Prone to harboring bacteria, leading to infection (although I’ve never had this happen after dozens of lid masses closed this way 🤞).
“Figure-8” closure (basically an upside-down cruciate). 
@conejovet

It is SO important to understand the difference between “good” and “bad” content regarding chimpanzees (primates) on social media. 
The difference can either lead to killing wild chimps and abducting baby chimps for the illegal pet trade (fueled by ‘bad’ content) or it can lead to chimp conservation thru awareness (promoted by ‘good’ content). 
Yes, YOU, can make a difference by being a little considerate about what you post, share, like, engage with because, good or bad, social media engagement DOES affect our wildlife. 
Big “thank you” to all of you that understand this and use social media with our wildlife in mind 🌍🙏

Repost from @janegoodallinst
•
We all like to ❤ chimpanzees, but did you know that some social content of chimpanzees that you “like” can be harmful? For #WorldChimpanzeeDay tomorrow (and every day) think twice before you like that chimpanzee social media post. *SHARE THESE GRAPHICS + SPREAD THE WORD.* You can also report inapprioraite content, by reporting > violence > animal abuse. 

Know the difference between good and bad content with our imagery guidelines, and hear more from Dr. Goodall LINK IN BIO!

node.text:
Do you know why we close the gums over extracted teeth❓
Dental extractions are very common in small animal veterinary medicine and when a tooth is diseased beyond repair they’re extracted. Sometimes more intricate surgical options are warranted with a species or tooth (i.e. endodontics, sealants, etc) but these are rarely performed outside of board certified dental specialists. Did you know dogs & cats living at home get by just fine with little to no teeth!?
Anyhow, we close the gingiva (aka gums) to prevent food particles and debri from entering the alveolar space (aka the pocket(s) where the extracted tooth’s root(s) previously occupied) bc that potential space + rotting food can lead to infection. Suturing the gingiva from the buccal (outer side) & lingual (inner side) pulls them over the alveolar spaces & blocks debri from entering. That space fills with blood clots and scar tissue, leaving a healthy mouth. 
Btw following the tooth extraction, but prior to suturing, I also use a dental drill to smooth out the sharp edges of the alveolar rim to reduce pain on chewing & healing complications, and to help appose both sides of the gums to close effectively. 
Dental disease affects 75+% of dogs & cats by just 2 years of age! If YOU have concerns about your pet’s dental health plz contact your local vet. Most people don’t realize their pet has dental disease to begin with and that’s another reason I highly encourage annual vet exams so we can catch these things!

node.text:
What if human doctors took pics with their patients immediately post op❓
Coco did very well with her dental procedure under anesthesia. Not bad for a 13 year old with breed/genetic heart disease! 
For those wondering - King Charles Cavalier Spaniels are highly predisposed to myxomatous degeneration of the mitral valve, often aka ‘mitral valve disease’. Luckily, managing her anesthetically didn’t give me any heart disease and I also have my trusty vet tech staff at @conejovet to thank for that.
FYI EVERY breed has at least 1 genetic related disease predisposition. Some dogs have several including German Shepherds (hip dysplasia, GI problems, including pancreatic enzymatic disease & GDV (gastric dilation & volvulus), allergies, obsessive compulsive workaholiciasis and more), English bulldogs (upper respiratory diseases, skin fold infections, allergies, osteoarthritis, corneal disease, flatulent olfactoffensive disorder), Yorkshire terriers (dental disease, luxating patellas, hepatic shunts, mitral valve disease, marked refractory stubbornatony), Shar Pei (Skin issues, occasional chronic-intermittent not-nice-to-their-veterinarrhea), Australian cattle dogs (severe epilepsy, unique drug sensitivities, moderate to severe too-smart-for-your-own-goodopathy), Labrador retrievers (ACL rupture, ear infections, chronic cerebral hyper enthusiasmophilia & secondary baseball-bat-tail-wagosis) and of course French bulldogs (cesarean section necessaragenesis, muppet-baby vocal dyskinesia, neonatal potato dumpling syndrome). 
Mixed breed dogs tend to have less genetic related issues compared to pure bred dogs and either way - if you have any concerns with your pet please contact your local vet!

Breba crop on a fig tree is the fruit produced by leftover nutrients in the previous season’s shoot growth & bark. 
My fig tree’s main seasonal fruit comes in Fall but these breba figs came in late Spring/Summer. Breba fruit is often not as sweet as main season fruit but this big feller was delicious 🍭.

node.text:
Tag that friend that reallyyyy loves wildlife 🐣
Idk the background of this giraffe and I can only speculate this behavior: I’ve seen healthy giraffes in captivity mouth/lick/bite on random objects for no obvious or concerning reason. Although it’s possible this behavior is secondary to pathology (dental disease, behavioral/stress, malnutrition, etc) my first inclination is to think this is a giraffe being silly as giraffes often are. 
I see tons of viral videos with animals exhibiting less familiar behaviors that appear ‘funny’ and/or ‘cute’ to most people (who aren’t knowledgeable about animals) and they don’t realize there’s a sad back-story. I can’t say with certainty, but I really do not believe that’s the case here.
